statement.p:
Find an equation of the curve that satisfies 
\frac{dy}{dx} = 80 yx^{9} 
and whose y-intercept is 6.

static.solution:
\displaystyle c_n = \frac{f^{(n)}(0)}{n!}, e.g. 



\displaystyle c_0 = \frac{f(0)}{0!} = 0. 



\displaystyle c_1 = \frac{f'(0)}{1!}; 



\displaystyle f'(x)=3 \arctan(7 x) + 3 x\frac{1}{(7 x)^2+1}7 
= 3 \arctan(7 x) + \frac{21 x}{49 x^2+1}; 



c_1 = 0.



\displaystyle c_2 = \frac{f''(0)}{2!}; 



\displaystyle 
f''(x) = \left( 3 \arctan(7 x) + \frac{21 x}{49 x^2+1} \right)' 



\displaystyle = 
\frac{21}{49 x^2+1} + \frac{21(49 x^2+1)-21 x49\cdot 2x}{(49 x^2+1)^2}



\displaystyle
= \frac{1029 x^2 + 21}{(49 x^2+1)^2} + \frac{21 - 1029 x^2}{(49 x^2+1)^2}
= \frac{42}{(49 x^2+1)^2};



\displaystyle c_2 = \frac{42}{2} = 21;



and so on. Another way is to use the power series for arctan:  



\displaystyle \arctan(t) = \sum_{n=0}^{\infty} (-1)^n \frac{t^{2n+1}}{2n+1} 
= t-\frac{t^3}{3}+\frac{t^5}{5}-\frac{t^7}{7}+....



Then 



\displaystyle 3 x \arctan(7 x) = 
3 x \sum_{n=0}^\infty (-1)^n \frac{(7 x)^{2n+1}}{2n+1} = 
\sum_{n=0}^\infty (-1)^n \frac{3\cdot 7^{2n+1}}{2n+1} x^{2n+2}
\displaystyle  
= 21 x^2 - \frac{1029}{3} x^4 + \frac{50421}{5} x^6 - \frac{2470629}{7} x^7+.... 



So c_0=0, c_1=0, c_2=21, c_3=0, c_4=-\frac{1029}{3}=-343...



This is an alternating series. It converges if and only if 
\displaystyle \lim_{n\to\infty}\frac{3 \cdot (7 x)^{2n+1}}{2n+1}=0. 
This limit is equal to 0 if and only if |7 x| \le 1, 
so \displaystyle |x|\le \frac{1}{7}. 
Therefore the radius of convergence is \displaystyle \frac{1}{7}.

